tually using multiple colors of light inside optical fibers that work at short range may help make computers smaller and faster miller the wm keck foundation professor of electrical engineering points out that while the business of telecommunications may have gotten ahead of the technology the technology's great potential remains for example he thinks the next big thing in photonics may well result from partnerships with biomedical scientists photonics he believes will be a major component in developing sensing devices that may one day perform an astounding number of tasks from screening patients for their genetic susceptibility to disease to testing them for their reactions to drugs before a prescription is written the field just emerging is called biophotonics there's lots of room for innovation miller says it's an exciting place to be it's got a long way to go and this is the right time to be doing it at the university last modified thu 12 jan 2012 at 9 24 stay connected itunes icon google+ icon facebook icon twitter icon linkedin icon stanford university school of engineering 475 via ortega stanford california 94305 4121 650.725 1575 1997 2012 stanford university all rights reserved accreditation info terms of use copyright complaints contact us
